  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — focusing strictly on future cash generation discounted to the present.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>GE Vernova delivered <strong>$3.71 billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. This is cash generated from operating activities after capital expenditures, reflecting true operational turnaround and strong momentum following its spin-off.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We project FCF to grow at <strong>15% per year</strong> for the next 5 years. GE Vernova benefits from immense secular tailwinds in electrification, grid modernization, and the global energy transition, allowing rapid FCF expansion as margins improve.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume a perpetual growth rate of <strong>2.5%</strong>. This captures long-term structural power demand growth, anchoring the terminal value using the Gordon Growth Model.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>Future cash flows are discounted at an <strong>8.5%</strong> WACC. We start with the 10-Year US Treasury yield of 4.18% and add an equity risk premium suitable for an established, large-cap industrial energy company.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value is aggregated and <strong>Net Cash ($8.85B)</strong> is added to find Equity Value. Dividing by the <strong>276 million</strong> diluted shares yields the intrinsic value per share.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>Our valuation relies on three fundamental assumptions.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">15%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        GE Vernova’s FCF jumped over 118% in FY2025 ($3.7B vs $1.7B in FY2024). While triple-digit growth won't persist, 15% is highly achievable as the company executes its massive backlog, modernizes grid infrastructure, and scales wind profitability.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">8.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Based on the current 10-Year US Treasury yield of 4.18%, plus an equity risk premium. An 8.5% rate is standard for an industrial company with a strong balance sheet and highly visible cash flows.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Matches long-term global GDP growth while reflecting ongoing, durable demand for global power generation and grid services well into the next decades.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (FY2025)</td>
          <td>${fcf2025.toLocaleString()}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year} ({2025 + p.year})</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
  <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Year 6 FCF (Year 5 × 1.025)</td>
